### Photo Plates (pp. 887-900)

*The plates document key figures and places in JDR's life.
Factual details from captions:*

#### Family & Origins
- **Lucy Avery Rockefeller** — JDR's grandmother, described
  as "doughty" — photo from Rockefeller Archive Center
- **JDR's birthplace** — humble farmhouse in
  **Richford, New York**
- **Five Rockefeller children** (William & Eliza's):
  Lucy (21), John (20), William (18), Mary Ann (16),
  Frank (14) — photo shows their relative ages at time
  of sitting
- **Lucy Henry Spelman** and **Harvey Buel Spelman**
  (JDR's in-laws) — caption notes both were
  "staunch temperance advocates and abolitionists"
- **Spelman sisters**: Lucy ("Lute") and Laura —
  described as "inseparable"

#### Oil Industry Origins
- **"Colonel" Edwin Drake** — photo at the landmark well
  he drilled in **Titusville, Pennsylvania, in 1859**;
  top-hatted figure standing before wooden derrick
  (Drake Well Museum)
- **Pithole** — oil boomtown that "sprang up miraculously
  in 1865 and vanished within a decade" — illustrates
  the chaos JDR sought to rationalize

#### Cleveland Properties
- **Rockefeller & Andrews** — occupied second-floor offices
  in the **Sexton Block**, Cleveland, after the Civil War
- **424 Euclid Avenue** — the "stately Rockefeller home"
  in Cleveland
- **Forest Hill** — the family's rambling retreat outside
  Cleveland, "briefly run by the family as a hotel"

#### Family Portraits
- **JDR studio portrait, 1884** — described as "polished"
- **Family picnic at Forest Hill, circa 1880**: JDR at far
  left; daughters **Bessie**, **Edith**, **Alta**;
  **Cettie** and Grandmother Spelman present
- **JDR camping, 1899** — "dines on sardines al fresco
  during an 1899 camping trip in the American West"
  — humanizing image of the world's richest man
- **Rockwood Hall** — brother **William Rockefeller**'s
  estate; JDR pictured there with daughter Alta and
  William's children Percy, Ethel, Emma

#### Philanthropy & Next Generation
- **Spelman Seminary first graduating class, 1887** —
  "founded to educate freed women slaves and their daughters"
- **John D. Rockefeller, Jr.** on his first pony —
  "hand-picked by his father"
- **JDR Jr. circa 1880** with "his sole childhood friend,
  Harry Moore, son of the Forest Hill housekeeper" —
  reveals the social isolation of JDR Jr.'s upbringing
- **Alta Rockefeller** on her wedding day to
  **Ezra Parmalee Prentice**

#### Key Associates & In-Laws
- **Harold Fowler McCormick** — captioned "dreamer and
  businessman" — married daughter Edith
- **Edith Rockefeller McCormick** — shown holding infant
  **John Rockefeller McCormick**, "whose early death from
  scarlet fever led to the founding of an institute for
  infectious diseases in Chicago"
- **Senator Nelson W. Aldrich** of Rhode Island —
  captioned with **Lincoln Steffens**'s label:
  "the political boss of the United States"
  — father-in-law of JDR Jr.
- **Abby Aldrich Rockefeller** (JDR Jr.'s wife) pictured
  with sisters Elsie and Lucy Aldrich, 1910

#### Manhattan Properties
- **4 West 54th Street** (Senior's house) and
  **10 West 54th Street** (Junior's grander adjoining
  house) — site now occupied by **Museum of Modern Art**
- The bedroom at 4 West 54th retained furnishings of
  predecessor **Arabella Worsham**, mistress of
  **Collis P. Huntington** — caption notes:
  "Such luxury was not their usual style"

#### Siblings & Key Adviser
- **William Rockefeller** — portrait (brother)
- **Frank Rockefeller** — portrait (estranged brother)
- **Frederick T. Gates** — portrait in later years;
  JDR's chief philanthropic adviser and gatekeeper

