## Photo Insert & Author Bio

### Photo Insert (No Prose — Visual Documentation)

Pages 901-920 are entirely a **photo insert section** followed by the author bio.
No narrative text or argument to capture. The photographs document key figures,
properties, and moments from the Rockefeller story.

### Key Figures Depicted

**Family — Senior Generation**
- **William Avery Rockefeller** (Big Bill) — only known photo with JDR Sr.,
  sitting "awkwardly" at a family portrait, circa 1897; buried under alias
  **"Dr. William Levingston"** in Freeport, Illinois (tombstone shown)
- **Eliza Davison Rockefeller** — aged portrait; caption notes she bore
  "a comical resemblance to her famous son in his later years"
- **John D. Rockefeller Sr.** — multiple late-life images:
  - Eerily hairless (alopecia), holding unidentified grandchild, Sept. 23, 1904
  - En route to testify in antitrust case, Nov. 18, 1908
  - In court escorted by **John G. Milburn** (Standard Oil lawyer)
  - At **Forest Hill** golf course with cronies: Dr. Hamilton F. Biggar,
    Elias M. Johnson, Capt. Levi T. Scofield, Dr. Charles A. Eaton
  - Strolling among sheep at **Golf House**, Lakewood, NJ (pastoral, incongruous)
  - Backseat of touring car flanked by two ladies (caption notes hands "often
    strayed during the afternoon drives" — oblique reference to his wandering
    touch in old age)
  - Sculpted by **Jo Davidson**, 1924 — "equally stony-faced"
  - Playing golf at **Ormond Beach**, Dec. 24, 1932, in trademark goggles
  - With daughter **Alta** at Ormond Beach, 1931
  - Seamed, leathery face in final decade, Dec. 17, 1931
  - Trading one-liners with **Will Rogers** at Ormond Beach, Feb. 1927
  - With **Bessie's** grandchildren Elizabeth and John de Cuevas, Ormond 1933

**Properties**
- **Kykuit** (Pocantico Hills estate): two versions shown
  - First version (1908) — found "wanting" by John and Cettie; demolished/rebuilt
  - Second version (1913) — more compact and elegant; open to public today
- **Golf House**, Lakewood, NJ — aerial view of golf hideaway
- **The Casements**, Ormond Beach, FL — winter home

**Media**
- Cover of ***McClure's Magazine*** featuring **Ida M. Tarbell**'s
  "character sketch" of JDR — described as "malevolent," deeply wounded
  Rockefeller

**Family — Junior Generation**
- **John D. Rockefeller Jr.** and **Abby Aldrich**, circa 1916
- Junior and Abby costumed for fancy dress ball at **Louis Tiffany**'s home,
  ~1910 (Athena + Middle Eastern robes — evidence the Rockefellers "could be
  playful on occasion")
- Junior leaving **Ludlow Massacre** hearings, NYC City Hall, Jan. 1915
- Junior testifying about Ludlow
- Junior with labor organizer **Mother Jones** at Jan. 27, 1915 hearings
  (impromptu encounter captured by photographer)
- Junior and Abby touring the **Grand Tetons**, Oct. 1931
- Junior greeting the **Rockettes** at **Radio City Music Hall**, Dec. 30, 1937
  (bashfully)

**Philanthropic Lieutenants** (group portrait of four key men)
- **Dr. Simon Flexner** — director, Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research
- **Wickliffe Rose** — head, Rockefeller Sanitary Commission
- **Starr J. Murphy** — legal adviser, Rockefeller Family Office
- **Wallace Buttrick** — secretary, General Education Board

**Business**
- **John D. Archbold** — "combative protégé and successor" to JDR at
  Standard Oil

**Third Generation**
- Abby + Junior with six children at Seal Harbor, Maine, 1921:
  **Laurance, Babs, John 3rd, David, Winthrop, Nelson**
- Sons in Eton collars: David, Winthrop, Laurance, Nelson, John 3rd
- Junior + Senior posing with **Nelson** and his first son, Rod-man
- Formal family dinner at **740 Park Avenue**, March 1949: Irving H. Pardee,
  David, Nelson, Winthrop, Laurance (standing); John 3rd and Junior (seated)
- Wives at same dinner: Abby (Babs) Rockefeller Pardee, Peggy McGrath
  Rockefeller, Mary "Tod" Rockefeller, Blanchette Hooker Rockefeller,
  Barbara "Bobo" Sears Rockefeller, Mary French Rockefeller

### Author Bio (Back Matter)

- **Ron Chernow** — prior books before *Titan*:
  - ***The House of Morgan*** — National Book Award; Ambassador Award;
    Modern Library top 100 nonfiction of the century
  - ***The Warburgs*** — Eccles Prize, Best Business Book of 1993;
    American Library Association notable nonfiction
  - ***The Death of the Banker*** (essays) — *NYT* called Chernow
    "as elegant an architect of monumental histories as we've seen in decades"

